| 1994 || {{dts|August}} || A detention center for juveniles opens in [[w:Leesport, Pennsylvania|Leesport]], [[w:Berks County, Pennsylvania|Berks County]], {{w|Pennsylvania}}. An article suggests that despite its distance from the border with Mexico, the location may have been chosen partly because of its convenience for government officials.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.ldnews.com/story/news/2017/06/16/why-pa-county-houses-central-american-immigrant-families/354842001/|title = Why a PA county houses Central American immigrant families|last = Moyer|first = Merriell|date = June 16, 2017|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Lebanon Daily News}}</ref> This detention center would become a family detention center in 2001.<ref name=readingeagle>{{cite web|url = https://www.readingeagle.com/news/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-residential-center-holding-immigrant-families-in-berks-county/article_597ea009-3706-5664-b1b4-4d0a3149edf5.html|title = What you need to know about the residential center holding immigrant families in Berks County|last = Shuey|first = Karen|last2 = Mekeel|first2 = David|last3 = Orozco|first3 = Anthony|date = June 24, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Reading Eagle}}</ref><ref name=billypenn>{{cite web|url = https://billypenn.com/2018/06/22/why-pas-controversial-detention-center-for-immigrant-families-is-still-open/|title = Why PA’s controversial Berks detention center for immigrant families is still open. A chorus of legislators and Philadelphia City Council are calling for the facility’s closure, as pressure mounts on Gov. Tom Wolf.|last = Deppen|first = Colin|last2 = Hughes|first2 = Sarah Ann|date = June 22, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = BillyPenn}}</ref>
|-
| 2001 || {{dts|March 3}} || The Berks County Residential Center in Leesport, Berks County, Pennsylvania switches from being a detention center for youth to a family detention center; Berks would be the first family detention center in the US.<ref name=readingeagle>{{cite web|url = https://www.readingeagle.com/news/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-residential-center-holding-immigrant-families-in-berks-county/article_597ea009-3706-5664-b1b4-4d0a3149edf5.html|title = What you need to know about the residential center holding immigrant families in Berks County|last = Shuey|first = Karen|last2 = Mekeel|first2 = David|last3 = Orozco|first3 = Anthony|date = June 24, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Reading Eagle}}</ref><ref name=billypenn>{{cite web|url = https://billypenn.com/2018/06/22/why-pas-controversial-detention-center-for-immigrant-families-is-still-open/|title = Why PA’s controversial Berks detention center for immigrant families is still open. A chorus of legislators and Philadelphia City Council are calling for the facility’s closure, as pressure mounts on Gov. Tom Wolf.|last = Deppen|first = Colin|last2 = Hughes|first2 = Sarah Ann|date = June 22, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = BillyPenn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://whyy.org/articles/lawyers-civic-groups-keep-the-pressure-on-berks-family-residential-center/|title = Lawyers, civic groups keep the pressure on Berks Family Residential Center|last = Orozco|first = Anthony|date = March 31, 2021|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = WHYY}}</ref>
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|June 24}} || DHS Secretary {{w|Jeh Johnson}} submits written testimony to the House Committee on Homeland Security detailing a multi-pronged response to the [[w:2014 American immigration crisis|2014 migrant surge]], particularly the surge in child migrants. Part of the strategy includes increasing detention capacity for children and for families. This would lead to a significant increase in the use of the Berks County Residential Center for family detention.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2014/06/24/written-testimony-dhs-secretary-jeh-johnson-house-committee-homeland-security|title = Written testimony of DHS Secretary Jeh Johnson for a House Committee on Homeland Security hearing titled “Dangerous Passage: The Growing Problem of Unaccompanied Children Crossing the Border”|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security|date = June 24, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021}}</ref><ref name=hrf-berks>{{cite web|url = https://www.humanrightsfirst.org/sites/default/files/HRF-Family-Det-Penn-rep-final.pdf|title = Family Detention in Berks County, Pennsylvania|date = August 1, 2015|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = Human Rights First}}</ref>
|-
| 2015 || {{dts|October}} || A Human Rights First report ''Family Detention: Still Happening, Still Damaging'' discusses the state of family detention in the United States, covering the three detention centers of Berks, Dilley, and Karnes.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.humanrightsfirst.org/sites/default/files/HRF-family-detention-still-happening.pdf|title = Family Detention: Still Happening, Still Damaging|date = October 1, 2015|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|January 21}} (announcement), {{dts|January 27}} (official notice) ||The Pennsylvania Department of Human Services (PA DHS) issues notice that the licensing of the Berks County Residential Center to operate as a child detention facility is being revoked and will not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/Resources/Documents/Pdf/ViolationReports/20160128_14386.pdf|title = The Department of Human Services is not renewing the certificate of compliance issued to the Berks County Commissioners to operate the Berks County Residential Center as a child residential facility|date = January 27, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www2.law.temple.edu/csj/publication/pennsylvanias-legal-authority-shut-berks-family-detention-center/|title = Pennsylvania’s legal authority to shut down Berks Family Detention Center|date = October 31, 2017|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Center for Social Justice, Temple University Beasley School of Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.readingeagle.com/2016/01/30/state-wont-renew-license-of-berks-county-residential-center/|title = State won’t renew license of Berks County Residential Center|date = January 30, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref> The decision would be appealed in February;<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/Resources/Documents/Pdf/ViolationReports/20160211_14386.pdf|title = This is to acknowledge receipt of your request to appeal the Department's decision to NON-RENEW and REVOKE the license for Berks County Residential Center.|date = February 8, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref> PA DHS would issue reports of violations to the Berks County Residential Center in the years from 2016 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/dhs/ViolationReport.aspx?reportid=14386&fac=BERKS%20COUNTY%20RESIDENTIAL%20CENTER#.WywNLlOUuRu|title = Inspection/Violation Reports for BERKS COUNTY RESIDENTIAL CENTER|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|February 22}} || In a blog post on the Immigration Impact bog, Lindsay Harris describes a recent visit to the Berks County Residential Center and connects the experiences in that visit with the recent decision by the Pennsylvania Department of Human Services to not renew Berks' license.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrationimpact.com/2016/02/22/berks-family-detention-center/|title = A Visit to Berks Family Detention Center Makes Clear Why They Lost their License|last = Harris|first = Lindsay|date = February 22, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Immigration Impact}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|April 15}} || Daniel Sharkey, a former guard at the Berks County Residential Center pleads guilty to and is sentenced for having a sexual relationship with a 19-year-old detainee from Honduras in 2014. Sexual relationships in such institutional settings are considered sexual assault, and consent by the victim is not a consideration; previous media reports suggested that the guard had threatened the victim with deportation if she told anybody about it.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.readingeagle.com/2016/04/15/west-reading-man-sentenced-for-sex-with-detainee/|title = West Reading man sentenced for sex with detainee|last = Weaver|first = Stephanie|date = April 15, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Reading Eagle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrationimpact.com/2016/04/15/berks-detention-center-employee-convicted-sexual-assault-young-honduran-mother/|title = Berks Detention Center Employee Convicted of Sexual Assault of Young Honduran Mother|last = Harris|first = Lindsay|date = April 15, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Immigration Impact}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|August 8}} || 22 female detainees (a group calling themselves "Madres de Berks") at Berks County Residential Center go on hunger strike to protest the length and conditions of their detention. Their statement says that they have been detained for 270 to 365 days, well above the "20 days or less" that DHS Secretary Jeh Johnson claims is the average length of stay in family detention.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.rt.com/usa/355774-detention-strike-hunger-mothers/|title = ‘We will get out alive or dead’: Migrant moms on hunger strike in US family detention center|publisher = Reuters|date = August 13, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/12/mothers-to-homeland-security-we-wont-eat-until-we-have-asylum/|title = Mothers to Homeland Security: We Won’t Eat Until We Are Released|author = Madres de Berks|date = August 12, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrationimpact.com/2016/08/15/mothers-hunger-strike-berks-family-detention-facility/|title = Why 22 Mothers Are On a Hunger Strike at the Berks Family Detention Facility|last = Feliz|first = Wendy|date = August 15, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Immigration Impact}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|December 11}} || The Sheller Center for Social Justice of the Beasley Law School of Temple University produces a legal memo outlining the legal powers of PA DHS and the Governor to close the Berks Detention Center.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://paimmigrant.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Sheller-Ctr-Legal-Memo.pdf|title = Pennsylvania Emergency Removal Order Authority|date = December 11, 2016|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2017 || {{dts|December 6}} || The Shut Down Berks Coalition Facebook page is created on this date.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.facebook.com/ShutDownBerksCoalition/|title = Shut Down Berks Coalition|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|January}} || The Shut Down Berks Twitter account, @ShutDownBerks, is created.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://twitter.com/ShutDownBerks|title = Shut Down Berks Coalition|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2019 || {{dts|December 11}} || Pennsylvania Auditor General Eugene DePasquale on Wednesday calls on ICE to stop detaining people at Berks, following his office’s report citing violations of federal law (specifically, the 20 day limit set by the Flores settlement) and risks for abuse at the facility.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.witf.org/2019/12/11/confinement-and-desperation-at-berks-immigrant-detainment-center-detailed-in-auditor-generals-report/|title = ‘Confinement and desperation’ at Berks County immigrant detention center detailed in auditor general’s report. U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement has twice denied requests to tour the Berks County Residential Center, where people are being kept for months while they await administrative hearings.|date = December 11, 2019|accessdate = December 18, 2021|last = Sholtis|first = Brett|publisher = WITF}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|January 23}} || Berks County settles, for $75,000, a lawsuit by a person who had been a victim of sexual assault at the facility in 2014 by then-guard Daniel Sharkey. Berks County denies the allegations in the lawsuit that other staff knew of the rape allegations, but decides to settle to avoid having its staff time used up in the lawsuit proceedings and also because they claim the victim deserves compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.mcall.com/news/pennsylvania/mc-nws-pa-berks-family-center-immigration-rape-trial-20200123-foju57hsvff43gwzmqhna2l7xu-story.html|title = Berks County will pay $75,000 to refugee who says she was sexually assaulted by worker at immigration center|last = Hall|first = Peter|date = January 23, 2020|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = The Morning Call}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|March}} || ICE announces that all families that were being held at the Berks County detention center are no longer being held there, and that the detention center will no longer be used for family detention. There are plans to use it for adult detention in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2021/03/03/Last-family-released-from-Berks-County-immigration-detention-center-pennsylvania/stories/202103030106|title = Last family released from Berks County immigration detention center|last = Hall|first = Peter|date = March 3, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = The Morning Call}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/us-says-it-will-stop-using-berks-co-detention-center-to-hold-migrant-families/2730911/|title = US Says It Will Stop Using Berks Co. Detention Center to Hold Migrant Families. The detention center in Pennsylvania will instead be used by ICE to hold adults, the government said|last = Merchant|first = Nomaan|date = March 6, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = NBC Philadelphia}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|March 30}} || A lawsuit is filed by the Sheller Center for Social Justice at Temple University Law School against Berks County commissioners Christian Leinbach, Kevin Barnhardt, and Michael Rivera, claiming that Berks County commissioners have been talking to ICE about converting the facility into an immigrant women’s prison but have refused to make any material public.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.inquirer.com/news/berks-immigrant-family-detention-center-ice-deportation-immigration-lawsuit-20210330.html|title = Immigration activists sue Berks commissioners to learn plans for ICE detention center. In March the center was emptied without explanation of the immigrant families it confined for two decades|last = Gammage|first = Jeff|date = March 30, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = The Philadelphia Inquirer}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|July 28}} || A letter to President {{w|Joe Biden}} and Vice-President {{w|Kamala Harris}} signed by over 50 Pennsylvania state and local officials urging the administration to not covert Berks into an immigration detention facility for adult women, citing the risk of abuse of detainees, and using the example of the T. Don Hutto Residential Center as a cautionary tale of a similar transformation.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.pahouse.com/files/Documents/2021-07-28_033911__BCDC%20Final%20(002).pdf|title = Re: Terminate ICE contract at the Berks County Residential Center|date = July 28, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.cityandstatepa.com/content/democrats-urge-feds-shut-down-berks-county-immigration-facility|title = Democrats urge feds to shut down Berks County immigration facility|date = July 29, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = City & State Pennsylvania|last = Sweitzer|first = Justin}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|September 25}} || Over 100 people gather in a rally at Independence Mall to protest plans to reopen the Berks County Residential Center as an immigration detention center for adult women.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.inquirer.com/news/berks-detention-center-immigration-rally-philadelphia-20210925.html|title = At Independence Hall, activists call for end of ICE contract and the plan for a women’s prison. “We believe that no one should be incarcerated for being a migrant,” said Adrianna Torres-Garcia, of the Free Migration Project.|date = September 25, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|last = Whelan|first = Aubrey|publisher = The Philadelphia Inquirer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theloquitur.com/the-center-on-immigration-joins-the-fight-to-shut-down-berks-and-to-support-haitian-immigrants/|title = The Center on Immigration joins the fight to shut down Berks and to support Haitian immigrants|last = Campos-Sánchez|first = Rodrigo|date = October 5, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|September 27}} || In an op-ed for ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', Adrianna Torres-Garcia, program coordinator for the Free Migration Project (one of the members of the Shut Down Berks Coalition) argues for the full shutdown of the Berks County detention center, as opposed to the current plan of turning it into an immigration detention center for adult women.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.inquirer.com/news/close-immigrant-detention-centers-berks-county-20210927.html|title = It’s time to close immigrant detention centers for good, not expand them. The move to expand a Berks County detention center is being driven by the Biden administration as part of their overall immigration plan, despite campaign promises to the contrary.|last = Torres-Garcia|first = Adrianna|date = September 27, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = The Philadelphia Inquirer}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|September 29}} || In an op-ed for ''Generocity'', Jasmine Rivera argues that the Berks County detention center should be fully shut down, as oppoosed to the current plan of turning it into an immigration detention center for adult women.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://generocity.org/philly/2021/09/29/opinion-its-time-to-permanently-close-berks-countys-immigrant-detention-center/|title = Opinion: It’s time to permanently close Berks County’s immigrant detention center. "As we speak, the Biden administration is pushing to turn the Berks County family prison into a women's prison," says guest columnist Jasmine Rivera.|last = Rivera|first = Jasmine|date = September 29, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Generocity}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|October 4}} || Congresswoman {{w|Madeleine Dean}}, in a letter to Pennsylvania Congressional colleagues, urges the Department of Homeland Security to Terminate the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) contract at the Berks County Residential Center.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://dean.house.gov/2021/10/congresswoman-madeleine-dean-leads-a-letter-to-terminate-ice-contract-at-the-berks-county-residential-center|title = Congresswoman Madeleine Dean Leads a Letter to Terminate ICE contract at the Berks County Residential Center|date = October 5, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
